## 1. The Big Picture — What is OAuth 2.0?

Think of OAuth 2.0 like a **hotel key card system**:

- You (the user) go to the **front desk** (Google/GitHub login page)
- You prove your identity to the front desk (enter your Google/GitHub credentials)
- The front desk gives you a **key card** (authorization code)
- You bring the key card back to the **hotel system** (your Spring Boot backend)
- The hotel system **verifies the key card** with the front desk (exchanges the code for an access token)
- The hotel system **gets your room details** (fetches your profile info from Google/GitHub)
- The hotel system creates **its own key** for you (a JWT token) so you don't need to go to the front desk again

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Your app **never sees** the user's Google/GitHub password. Google/GitHub only give you a token to read the user's profile. That's the whole point of OAuth — **delegated authorization**.

---

## 2. The Complete Flow — Step by Step

Here's exactly what happens when a user clicks "Login with Google":

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant B as Browser
    participant FE as Frontend :3000
    participant BE as Spring Boot :8080
    participant G as Google

    Note over B: Step 1: User clicks "Login with Google"
    B->>BE: GET /oauth2/authorization/google

    Note over BE: Step 2: Spring Security generates Google login URL
    BE->>B: 302 Redirect to accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?client_id=xxx&redirect_uri=xxx&scope=openid+profile+email

    Note over B: Step 3: Google shows login page
    B->>G: User enters Google credentials
    G->>G: Google verifies password

    Note over G: Step 4: Google redirects back with authorization code
    G->>B: 302 Redirect to localhost:8080/login/oauth2/code/google?code=AUTHORIZATION_CODE

    Note over BE: Step 5: Spring Security intercepts this callback
    B->>BE: GET /login/oauth2/code/google?code=AUTHORIZATION_CODE

    Note over BE: Step 6: Spring exchanges code for access token (server-to-server)
    BE->>G: POST https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token (with code + client_secret)
    G->>BE: Returns access_token

    Note over BE: Step 7: Spring uses access token to get user info
    BE->>G: GET https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v3/userinfo (with access_token)
    G->>BE: Returns {sub, email, name, picture}

    Note over BE: Step 8: CustomOAuth2UserService.loadUser() is called
    Note over BE: → Creates or finds user in MongoDB
    Note over BE: Step 9: OAuth2SuccessHandler.onAuthenticationSuccess() is called
    Note over BE: → Generates JWT token

    Note over BE: Step 10: Redirect to frontend with JWT
    BE->>B: 302 Redirect to localhost:3000/oauth2/callback?token=JWT&username=xxx

    Note over FE: Step 11: Frontend stores JWT
    B->>FE: Page loads, extracts token from URL
    FE->>FE: localStorage.setItem("token", JWT)

    Note over B: Step 12: All future API calls use JWT (same as before)
    FE->>BE: GET /api/rooms (Authorization: Bearer JWT)
```

### The key thing to understand:
- **Steps 2-7 are handled automatically by Spring Security** — you don't write any code for this
- **Step 8** is your [CustomOAuth2UserService](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/Springboot/ChatApp/src/main/java/com/project/ChatApp/service/CustomOAuth2UserService.java#16-91) — where YOU decide what to do with the user info
- **Step 9** is your [OAuth2SuccessHandler](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/Springboot/ChatApp/src/main/java/com/project/ChatApp/config/OAuth2SuccessHandler.java#21-89) — where YOU generate the JWT and redirect
- **Steps 1 and 10-12** happen on the frontend

